Hamiltonian orbits in elliptical bowls

December 29, 2016 at 20:05

  • Integer ratios
    • Spherical bowl
      • Dropped puck
    • Elliptical bowls
      • Dropped pucks
  • Some fractional ratios (between 1 and 3/2)
  • Fractional ratios: multiples of 1/2
  • Fractional ratios: multiples of 1/3
  • Fractional ratios: multiples of 1/4
  • Irrational ratios: multiples of \(\pi/2\)

Integer ratios

The number of self-crossings is one less than the ratio.

The symmetry is reflective through the minor axis for even ratios and rotational through 180 degrees for even ratios.

Spherical bowl

ratio <- 1; x<- c(12,6); m <- p2c(3, -pi/4)
orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m)

Dropped puck

orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, 0)

Elliptical bowls

ratio <- 2; orbit(ratio*2, 2, x, m)

ratio <- 3; orbit(ratio, 1, x, m) 

ratio <- 4; orbit(ratio, 1, x, m) 

ratio <- 5; orbit(ratio, 1, x, m) 

ratio <- 6; orbit(ratio, 1, x, m)

Dropped pucks

ratio <- 2; orbit(ratio*2, 2, x, 0) 

ratio <- 3; orbit(ratio, 1, x, 0) 

ratio <- 4; orbit(ratio, 1, x, 0) 

ratio <- 5; orbit(ratio, 1, x, 0) 

ratio <- 6; orbit(ratio, 1, x, 0)

Some fractional ratios (between 1 and 3/2)

ratio <- 3/2; x<- c(12,6); m <- p2c(3, -pi/4)
orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m) 

ratio <- 4/3; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m) 

ratio <- 5/4; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m) 

ratio <- 6/5; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100) 

ratio <- 7/6; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 200) 

ratio <- 8/7; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 200)

Fractional ratios: multiples of 1/2

These patterns show symmetry through reflection in the major axis

ratio <- 3/2; x<- c(12,6); m <- p2c(3, 6*pi/4)
orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m) 

ratio <- 4/2; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m) 

ratio <- 5/2; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100) 

ratio <- 6/2; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100) 

ratio <- 7/2; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100)

Fractional ratios: multiples of 1/3

These patterns exhibit rotational symmetry through rotation by 180 degrees

Note that the ratio 7/2 produces 32 self-crossings. I tried a variety of conditions and always got 32 self-crossings, except when the curve retraces over itself.

ratio <- 4/3; x<- c(12,6); m <- p2c(6, 3*pi/4)
orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m) 

ratio <- 5/3; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100) 

ratio <- 7/3; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100)

Fractional ratios: multiples of 1/4

These patterns exhibit rotational symmetry through reflection in the major axis

ratio <- 5/4; x<- c(12,6); m <- p2c(3, 2*pi/4)
orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 80)  # 30 x

ratio <- 6/4; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100) 

ratio <- 7/4; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 100) # rotational symmetry by 180 degrees

Irrational ratios: multiples of \(\pi/2\)

These patterns exhibit rotational symmetry through reflection in the major axis

ratio <- pi/2; x<- c(12,6); m <- p2c(3, -pi/4)
orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 200)  # 30 x

ratio <- 2*pi/2; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 200) 

ratio <- 3*pi/2; orbit(ratio*3, 3, x, m, imax = 200)
